  "chunk_index": 15,
  "summary": "Viscountess Kettelbach encourages Bondel to pursue a career in politics and suggests she meet an influential woman named Mrs. McCarta. When Bondel mentions that her father did not invite her to George Lomax's upcoming house party, the Viscountess promises to speak with Lomax to ensure Bondel's attendance. After receiving political research materials from the Viscountess's secretary, Bondel contacts Jimmy Sexton. Jimmy reveals he is researching the Santa Fe border dispute and studying a note sent from Bolivia to Britain. The two agree to keep their respective research secret from Lorena Wade to protect her from potential danger. As Bondel prepares for an autopsy scheduled for the following day, Jimmy plans to take Lorena to dinner.\n\nBondel later travels to the Seven Dials Club at 14 Hanstein Street, wearing borrowed clothes to disguise herself. Her objective is to confront her former butler, Alfred. She intercepts Alfred as he is exiting the club and insists on speaking with him inside. Bondel accuses him of illegal activities and demands to know how much he was paid to leave the Chimney House. Alfred admits that a Russian gentleman named Mr. Mosgrove, who runs the club, paid him £100 and instructed him to manage the club to provide it with more \"class.\" Alfred explains that Mosgrove also arranged for a replacement servant at the Chimney House. Bondel warns Alfred about the risks of forced labor and mentions her visit to Scotland Yard, promising to protect him if he agrees to assist her investigation.",
